=> Key Terminology:
    -> Event: What happened
    -> Event Source: Where event took place
    -> Topic: The endpoint where publishers send events
    -> Event Subscriptions: The endpoint or built-in mechanism to route events, sometimes to more than one handler.
    -> Event Handler: The app or service reacting to the event.

=> Azure Event Grid

    -> Overview:
        -> Azure Event Grid is a fully managed event-based (Pub/Sub) messaging service.
        -> Used to build event-driven architectures.
        -> Supports:
            -> HTTP (for apps/services)
            -> MQTT (for IoT devices)

        -> Enables:
            -> Application integration
            -> Real-time event processing
            -> Serverless architectures

    -> Core Concept (Pub/Sub Model):

        -> Publisher → Sends events
        -> Event Grid → Routes events
        -> Subscriber → Receives events

    -> Key Concepts:

        -> Publisher:
            -> Source that sends events
            -> Can be:
                -> Azure services (Storage, IoT Hub)
                -> Custom applications
                -> External systems (partners)

        -> Event:
            -> A small piece of data describing something that happened
            -> Contains:
                -> Source
                -> Time
                -> Unique ID
                -> Event-specific data

        -> Event Source:
            -> Where the event is generated
            -> Examples:
                -> Blob Storage → Blob created event
                -> IoT Hub → Device event
                -> Custom app → Custom event

        -> Topics:
            -> Logical channel to store and organize events

            -> Types:
                -> System Topics:
                    -> Built-in (Azure services)
                    -> Not visible in your subscription

                -> Custom Topics:
                    -> Created by user
                    -> Used for custom applications

                -> Partner Topics:
                    -> Used for third-party integrations

        -> Event Subscription:
            -> Defines which events you want to receive
            -> Includes:
                -> Endpoint (where event is sent)
                -> Filters (event type, subject)
                -> Expiration (optional)

        -> Event Handler:
            -> Destination that processes events
            -> Examples:
                -> Azure Functions
                -> Logic Apps
                -> Webhooks
                -> Storage Queue

            -> Behavior:
                -> Retries until success (e.g., HTTP 200 OK)

    -> Event Format:

        -> Uses CloudEvents 1.0 standard
        -> JSON format
        -> Includes metadata + actual data

    -> Delivery Modes:

        -> Push Model:
            -> Event Grid sends events to subscriber automatically

        -> Pull Model:
            -> Subscriber reads events from Event Grid

    -> Security:

        -> Uses Microsoft Entra ID for authentication
        -> Managed Identity can be used for secure access
        -> RBAC roles control permissions

    -> Key Flow:

        -> Event Source → Publishes Event
        -> Event → Stored in Topic
        -> Subscription → Filters Event
        -> Event Grid → Sends to Handler
        -> Handler → Processes Event

    -> Key Points:

        -> Highly scalable and serverless
        -> Supports filtering and routing
        -> Near real-time event delivery

=> Azure Event Grid: Event Schemas

    -> Overview:
        -> Event Grid supports two types of schemas:
            -> Event Grid Schema (default)
            -> CloudEvents Schema (standard/open format)

        -> Schema defines:
            -> Structure/format of an event (JSON)

    -> Event Structure (General):

        -> Events are sent as:
            -> Array of events

        -> Size Limits:
            -> Max size per event = 1 MB
            -> Max size per array = 1 MB
            -> > 1 MB → Error (413 Payload Too Large)

        -> Billing:
            -> Charged per 64 KB
            -> Example:
                -> 130 KB event = counted as 3 operations

    -> Event Grid Schema (Default):

        -> Common Properties (Top-Level):

            -> topic:
                -> Resource path of event source

            -> subject:
                -> Path or identifier of event (used for filtering)

            -> eventType:
                -> Type of event (e.g., BlobCreated)

            -> eventTime:
                -> Time when event occurred (UTC)

            -> id:
                -> Unique identifier for event

            -> data:
                -> Actual event data (custom per service)

            -> dataVersion:
                -> Version of data schema

            -> metadataVersion:
                -> Version of event metadata (fixed by Event Grid)
    -> Example:
        [
          {
            "topic": string,
            "subject": string,
            "id": string,
            "eventType": string,
            "eventTime": string,
            "data":{
              object-unique-to-each-publisher
            },
            "dataVersion": string,
            "metadataVersion": string
          }
        ]

    -> Important Notes:

        -> All events share same top-level structure
        -> Only "data" field changes based on event source
        -> Subject is very important for filtering

    -> Subject Design (Best Practice):

        -> Use hierarchical format:
            -> Example: /A/B/C

        -> Benefits:
            -> Easy filtering
            -> Flexible routing

        -> Example:
            -> /blobServices/default/containers/container1/blobs/file.txt

        -> Filtering:
            -> /A → broad filtering
            -> /A/B → more specific filtering

    -> CloudEvents Schema:

        -> Open standard (Cloud Native Computing Foundation)
        -> Used for interoperability across platforms

        -> Key Fields:

            -> specversion:
                -> Version of CloudEvents spec

            -> type:
                -> Event type

            -> source:
                -> Origin of event

            -> id:
                -> Unique event ID

            -> time:
                -> Event time

            -> subject:
                -> Event subject/path

            -> data:
                -> Actual payload

            -> dataschema:
                -> Schema reference
    -> Example:
        {
            "specversion": "1.0",
            "type": "Microsoft.Storage.BlobCreated",
            "source": "/subscriptions/{subscription-id}/resourceGroups/{resource-group}/providers/Microsoft.Storage/storageAccounts/{storage-account}",
            "id": "9aeb0fdf-c01e-0131-0922-9eb54906e209",
            "time": "2019-11-18T15:13:39.4589254Z",
            "subject": "blobServices/default/containers/{storage-container}/blobs/{new-file}",
            "dataschema": "#",
            "data": {
                "api": "PutBlockList",
                "clientRequestId": "4c5dd7fb-2c48-4a27-bb30-5361b5de920a",
                "requestId": "9aeb0fdf-c01e-0131-0922-9eb549000000",
                "eTag": "0x8D76C39E4407333",
                "contentType": "image/png",
                "contentLength": 30699,
                "blobType": "BlockBlob",
                "url": "https://gridtesting.blob.core.windows.net/testcontainer/{new-file}",
                "sequencer": "000000000000000000000000000099240000000000c41c18",
                "storageDiagnostics": {
                    "batchId": "681fe319-3006-00a8-0022-9e7cde000000"
                }
            }
        }

    -> Event Grid vs CloudEvents:

        -> Event Grid Schema:
            -> Azure-specific
            -> Default format

        -> CloudEvents Schema:
            -> Standard format
            -> Better for cross-platform integration

    -> Content-Type Header:

        -> Event Grid:
            -> application/json

        -> CloudEvents:
            -> application/cloudevents+json

    -> Key Points:

        -> Event = metadata + actual data
        -> "data" field varies per service
        -> Subject helps in filtering
        -> CloudEvents improves interoperability

=> Azure Event Grid: Event Delivery & Durability

    -> Overview:
        -> Event Grid provides durable delivery of events
        -> Guarantee:
            -> At-least-once delivery (event may be delivered multiple times)

        -> Note:
            -> Event order is NOT guaranteed

    -> Delivery Behavior:

        -> Event Grid sends:
            -> One event at a time (default)
            -> Payload is an array with single event

        -> If delivery fails:
            -> Event Grid retries delivery

    -> Retry Mechanism:

        -> Default:
            -> Immediate attempt
            -> Then retries using exponential backoff

        -> Timeout:
            -> Waits 30 seconds for response
            -> If no response → retry scheduled

        -> If endpoint responds within 3 minutes:
            -> Event removed from retry queue (best effort)
            -> Duplicate delivery still possible

    -> No Retry Cases (Important):

        -> Retry does NOT happen for:

            -> Azure Resources:
                -> 400 (Bad Request)
                -> 413 (Payload Too Large)

            -> Webhooks:
                -> 400, 413, 401 (Unauthorized)

        -> Behavior:
            -> If Dead-letter enabled → event stored
            -> Else → event dropped ❌

    -> Retry Policy (Configurable):

        -> Max Delivery Attempts:
            -> Range: 1 to 30
            -> Default: 30

        -> Time-To-Live (TTL):
            -> Range: 1 to 1440 minutes
            -> Default: 1440 minutes (24 hours)

        -> Event is dropped if:
            -> Max attempts reached OR TTL expired

    -> Dead-Lettering:

        -> Definition:
            -> Store undelivered events in Storage Account

        -> Trigger Conditions:
            -> Retry attempts exceeded
            -> TTL expired
            -> Certain errors (400, 413)

        -> Notes:
            -> Must be manually enabled
            -> Requires Storage Account + container
            -> If storage unavailable for 4 hours → event dropped

    -> Delayed Delivery:

        -> If endpoint keeps failing:
            -> Event Grid delays further delivery

        -> Purpose:
            -> Prevent overload of unhealthy systems

        -> Delay can increase up to several hours

    -> Output Batching:

        -> Purpose:
            -> Improve performance for high volume

        -> Settings:

            -> Max Events per Batch:
                -> Range: 1 to 5000

            -> Preferred Batch Size:
                -> Defined in KB

        -> Notes:
            -> Batching is optional (disabled by default)
            -> Events are not delayed just to form batch

    -> Custom Delivery Headers:

        -> You can add custom HTTP headers
        -> Max:
            -> 10 headers
            -> Each ≤ 4096 bytes

        -> Used for:
            -> Authentication
            -> Custom routing

    -> Key Points:

        -> At-least-once delivery → duplicates possible
        -> No guarantee of order
        -> Retry + Dead-letter = reliability
        -> Configure retry policy as per requirement

=> Azure Event Grid: Access Control (RBAC)

    -> Overview:
        -> Event Grid uses Azure RBAC to control access
        -> Controls who can:
            -> Create topics
            -> Manage subscriptions
            -> Send events

    -> Built-in Roles:

        -> Event Grid Subscription Reader:
            -> Read event subscriptions only

        -> Event Grid Subscription Contributor:
            -> Create, update, delete event subscriptions

        -> Event Grid Contributor:
            -> Full control over Event Grid resources
            -> Can create/manage topics

        -> Event Grid Data Sender:
            -> Can publish/send events to topics

    -> Key Understanding:

        -> Subscription roles:
            -> Only manage subscriptions
            -> Cannot create topics

        -> Contributor role:
            -> Full resource-level control

    -> Permissions for Event Subscription:

        -> Required Permission:
            -> Microsoft.EventGrid/EventSubscriptions/Write

        -> Why required?
            -> To create a new event subscription
            -> Prevent unauthorized event routing

    -> Based on Topic Type:

        -> System Topic:
            -> Permission required on:
                -> Event Source Resource

            -> Resource Format:
                -> /subscriptions/{subscription-id}/resourceGroups/{resource-group-name}/providers/{resource-provider}/{resource-type}/{resource-name}

            -> Example:
                -> Storage Account
                -> IoT Hub

            -> Meaning:
                -> You need access on the actual Azure resource generating events

        -> Custom Topic:
            -> Permission required on:
                -> Event Grid Topic

            -> Resource Format:
                -> /subscriptions/{subscription-id}/resourceGroups/{resource-group-name}/providers/Microsoft.EventGrid/topics/{topic-name}

            -> Meaning:
                -> You need access directly on the Event Grid topic

    -> Key Points:

        -> RBAC controls access at resource level
        -> Permission required depends on topic type
        -> Write permission needed to create subscription

=> Receive Events using Webhooks (Azure Event Grid)

    -> What is a Webhook?

        -> A webhook is an HTTP endpoint (URL) that receives events via HTTP POST request
        -> Event Grid sends event data to this endpoint when an event occurs

        -> Simple Meaning:
            -> "Event happens → HTTP call is triggered automatically"

    -> How Webhook Works:

        -> Step 1:
            -> Event occurs (Publisher)

        -> Step 2:
            -> Event Grid receives event

        -> Step 3:
            -> Event Grid sends HTTP POST request

        -> Step 4:
            -> Webhook endpoint receives event data

    -> Use Cases:

        -> Trigger custom backend logic
        -> Integrate with external systems
        -> Real-time notifications
        -> Example:
            -> File uploaded → Call API → Send email
            -> Order created → Notify external service

    -> Supported Services (Auto Validation):

        -> Azure handles validation automatically for:
            -> Azure Functions (Event Grid Trigger)
            -> Azure Logic Apps
            -> Azure Automation

    -> Endpoint Validation (Important):

        -> Why validation needed?
            -> To verify endpoint ownership
            -> Prevent malicious event flooding

    -> Validation Methods:

        -> 1. Synchronous Handshake:

            -> Event Grid sends:
                -> Validation Event (with validationCode)

            -> Your endpoint must:
                -> Read validationCode
                -> Return same code in response

            -> Requirement:
                -> Must respond immediately

        -> 2. Asynchronous Handshake:

            -> Used when:
                -> Endpoint cannot respond immediately (e.g., third-party tools)

            -> Event Grid sends:
                -> validationUrl

            -> You must:
                -> Perform GET request on validationUrl

            -> Conditions:
                -> Valid only for 5 minutes
                -> Subscription state = AwaitingManualAction

            -> If not completed:
                -> Subscription = Failed ❌

    -> HTTP Requirements:

        -> Endpoint must return:
            -> HTTP 200 OK

        -> Otherwise:
            -> Validation fails

    -> Important Notes:

        -> Event Grid sends events via HTTP POST
        -> Validation is mandatory before receiving events
        -> Self-signed certificates are NOT supported
        -> Use valid SSL certificate (CA-signed)

    -> Key Points:

        -> Webhook = Event receiver (HTTP endpoint)
        -> Used for real-time integrations
        -> Validation ensures security

=> Filter Events (Azure Event Grid)

    -> Why Filtering?

        -> Not all events are useful
        -> Filtering allows you to receive only required events
        -> Reduces unnecessary processing and cost

    -> Types of Filtering:

        -> 1. Event Type Filtering
        -> 2. Subject Filtering
        -> 3. Advanced Filtering

    ----------------------------------------------------

    -> 1. Event Type Filtering

        -> By default:
            -> All event types are sent to subscriber

        -> You can filter:
            -> Only specific event types

        -> Example:
            -> Only want success events, not delete events

        -> Syntax:

            "filter": {
              "includedEventTypes": [
                "Microsoft.Resources.ResourceWriteFailure",
                "Microsoft.Resources.ResourceWriteSuccess"
              ]
            }

        -> Special Case:
            -> "All" → Receive all event types

    ----------------------------------------------------

    -> 2. Subject Filtering

        -> Used for simple string-based filtering

        -> Based on:
            -> subjectBeginsWith
            -> subjectEndsWith

        -> Example Use Case:
            -> Only .txt files
            -> Only specific container

        -> Syntax:

            "filter": {
              "subjectBeginsWith": "/blobServices/default/containers/mycontainer/log",
              "subjectEndsWith": ".jpg"
            }

        -> Example Meaning:
            -> Only events from "mycontainer/log"
            -> Only files ending with ".jpg"

    ----------------------------------------------------

    -> 3. Advanced Filtering

        -> Used for complex conditions

        -> Allows filtering on:
            -> Event data fields
            -> Subject
            -> Custom values

        -> Components:

            -> operatorType:
                -> Type of comparison
                -> Example:
                    -> NumberGreaterThan
                    -> StringContains
                    -> BooleanEquals

            -> key:
                -> Field in event data
                -> Example:
                    -> Data.Key1
                    -> Subject

            -> value / values:
                -> Value to compare

        -> Syntax:

            "filter": {
              "advancedFilters": [
                {
                  "operatorType": "NumberGreaterThanOrEquals",
                  "key": "Data.Key1",
                  "value": 5
                },
                {
                  "operatorType": "StringContains",
                  "key": "Subject",
                  "values": ["container1", "container2"]
                }
              ]
            }

        -> Example Meaning:

            -> First condition:
                -> Data.Key1 >= 5

            -> Second condition:
                -> Subject contains "container1" OR "container2"

    ----------------------------------------------------

    -> Key Points:

        -> Event Type → Filter based on event name
        -> Subject → Filter based on path/string
        -> Advanced → Filter based on data values

        -> Filters help:
            -> Reduce unwanted events
            -> Improve performance
            -> Save cost

=> Azure Event Hubs

    -> What is Event Hubs?

        -> Azure Event Hubs is a cloud-based data streaming platform
        -> It can handle millions of events per second with low latency
        -> Used for real-time data ingestion and processing

        -> Simple Meaning:
            -> "Collect and process huge streams of data in real-time"

    -> Use Cases:

        -> IoT data ingestion (device telemetry)
        -> Application logs & monitoring
        -> Real-time analytics
        -> Clickstream data (user activity tracking)

    ----------------------------------------------------

    -> Key Features:

        -> High Throughput:
            -> Can process millions of events per second

        -> Low Latency:
            -> Near real-time processing

        -> Scalable:
            -> Uses partitions to scale

        -> Kafka Compatible:
            -> Can run Apache Kafka apps without code change

        -> Protocol Support:
            -> AMQP, Kafka, HTTPS

    ----------------------------------------------------

    -> Key Concepts:

        -> 1. Producer

            -> Sends data/events to Event Hub
            -> Example:
                -> IoT device
                -> Application logs

        -> 2. Namespace

            -> Container for Event Hubs
            -> Used for:
                -> Security
                -> Scaling
                -> Configuration

        -> 3. Event Hub / Kafka Topic

            -> Logical stream of events
            -> Acts like:
                -> Append-only log

        -> 4. Partitions

            -> Used for scalability
            -> More partitions = more parallel processing

            -> Analogy:
                -> Multiple lanes on highway 🚗

        -> 5. Consumer

            -> Reads events from Event Hub
            -> Maintains its own offset (position)

        -> 6. Consumer Group

            -> Group of consumers
            -> Each group reads data independently

            -> Benefit:
                -> Multiple applications can read same data

    ----------------------------------------------------

    -> Important Concepts:

        -> Offset:

            -> Position of consumer in event stream
            -> Helps track which events are read

        -> Partitioned Model:

            -> Data is distributed across partitions
            -> Enables parallel processing

    ----------------------------------------------------

    -> Advanced Features:

        -> Apache Kafka Support:

            -> Run Kafka apps directly on Event Hubs
            -> No need to manage Kafka clusters

        -> Schema Registry:

            -> Central place to store event schemas
            -> Ensures consistent data format

        -> Stream Analytics Integration:

            -> Real-time processing using:
                -> Drag & drop (no code)
                -> SQL-like queries

    ----------------------------------------------------

    -> Flow (End-to-End):

        Producer → Event Hub → Partition → Consumer Group → Consumer

    ----------------------------------------------------

    -> Key Points:

        -> Event Hubs = Big data streaming service
        -> Handles high volume real-time data
        -> Supports multiple consumers
        -> Scalable using partitions

=> Event Hubs Capture

    -> What is Event Hubs Capture?

        -> Event Hubs Capture is a feature of Azure Event Hubs
        -> It automatically stores streaming data into storage

        -> Supported Storage:
            -> Azure Blob Storage
            -> Azure Data Lake Storage

        -> Simple Meaning:
            -> "Automatically save streaming data into storage without writing code"

    ----------------------------------------------------

    -> Why Capture is used?

        -> To store real-time streaming data
        -> To enable batch processing later
        -> To build hybrid systems (real-time + batch)

        -> Example:
            -> IoT data → stored in Blob → later analyzed in Spark

    ----------------------------------------------------

    -> How Event Hubs Capture Works?

        -> Event Hub acts like a buffer (temporary storage)

        -> Flow:

            Producer → Event Hub → Capture → Blob Storage / Data Lake

        -> Key idea:
            -> Data is continuously collected and stored automatically

    ----------------------------------------------------

    -> Partition-based Storage Model

        -> Event Hubs is partitioned

        -> Each partition:
            -> Captures data independently
            -> Stores its own output file

        -> Benefit:
            -> Parallel processing
            -> High scalability

    ----------------------------------------------------

    -> Capture Windowing

        -> Capture is controlled using time or size window

        -> Example:
            -> Every 5 minutes OR 100 MB data

        -> First trigger wins policy:
            -> Whichever condition hits first triggers capture

        -> Output format:
            -> Data written as files (block blobs)

    ----------------------------------------------------

    -> File Naming Convention:

        -> Format:

        {Namespace}/{EventHub}/{PartitionId}/{Year}/{Month}/{Day}/{Hour}/{Minute}/{Second}

        -> Example:

        https://storage.blob.core.windows.net/container/
        mynamespace/myeventhub/0/2017/12/08/03/03/17.avro

    ----------------------------------------------------

    -> Data Format Used:

        -> Apache Avro format

        -> Why Avro?

            -> Compact (small size)
            -> Fast processing
            -> Binary format
            -> Includes schema with data

    ----------------------------------------------------

    -> Scaling Concept:

        -> Event Hubs uses Throughput Units (TU)

        -> Each TU provides:

            -> 1 MB/sec ingestion (~1000 events/sec)
            -> 2 MB/sec egress

        -> Scaling options:

            -> Increase TUs manually
            -> Auto-inflate (auto scaling)

    ----------------------------------------------------

    -> Important Behavior:

        -> Capture runs automatically once enabled

        -> No manual trigger required

        -> If no data arrives:
            -> Empty files are created

        -> Purpose of empty files:
            -> Maintain processing consistency in batch systems

    ----------------------------------------------------

    -> Key Benefits:

        -> No code required for storage
        -> Real-time + batch processing support
        -> Automatic scaling
        -> Works with big data tools (Spark, Data Factory)

=> Scale Your Event Processing Application (Azure Event Hubs)

    -> Why Scaling is Needed?

        -> Event Hubs can receive millions of events per second
        -> One consumer is not enough to process all data
        -> So we need multiple consumer instances

    ----------------------------------------------------

    -> Core Concept: Partitioned Consumer Model

        -> Event Hub data is split into partitions
        -> Each partition is processed independently

        -> Key Idea:
            -> One partition → One active consumer at a time

        -> Benefit:
            -> Parallel processing
            -> High scalability
            -> No contention between consumers

    ----------------------------------------------------

    -> Older vs New SDKs:

        -> Old Model:
            -> EventProcessorHost

        -> New Model (Recommended):

            -> .NET / Java:
                -> EventProcessorClient

            -> Python / JavaScript:
                -> EventHubConsumerClient

    ----------------------------------------------------

    -> Real-Life Scenario Example:

        -> 100,000 homes with sensors
        -> Each sensor sends events every minute

        -> Event Hub:
            -> 16 partitions

        -> Consumer App:
            -> Reads data
            -> Aggregates it
            -> Stores in Blob Storage
            -> Shows on dashboard

    ----------------------------------------------------

    -> Requirements in Distributed Consumer System:

        -> 1. Scale

            -> Add multiple consumer instances
            -> Each instance processes few partitions

        -> 2. Load Balancing

            -> If traffic increases:
                -> Add more consumers

            -> System automatically redistributes partitions

        -> 3. Failure Handling (Resilience)

            -> If consumer crashes:
                -> Another consumer takes over its partitions

            -> Processing continues from last saved position

        -> 4. Event Processing

            -> Consume event
            -> Process data
            -> Store / transform / route

    ----------------------------------------------------

    -> Event Processor Client (Managed Solution)

        -> Provided by Azure SDK
        -> Handles:
            -> Load balancing
            -> Partition assignment
            -> Failover
            -> Coordination

    ----------------------------------------------------

    -> Partition Ownership Tracking

        -> Each consumer has a unique ID

        -> How it works:

            -> Consumers write ownership info to checkpoint store
            -> All consumers read this shared store
            -> System decides partition distribution

        -> Result:
            -> Even load distribution across consumers

    ----------------------------------------------------

    -> Checkpointing

        -> What is Checkpoint?

            -> Saving last processed event position (offset)

        -> Why needed?

            -> If consumer fails
            -> Another consumer resumes from same position

        -> Flow:

            Event → Process → Save Offset (Checkpoint)

        -> Benefits:

            -> No data loss
            -> Resume processing safely
            -> Fault tolerance

    ----------------------------------------------------

    -> Receive Event Behavior:

        -> Each event processed one by one per partition
        -> Sequential processing per partition

        -> Across partitions:
            -> Parallel processing allowed

    ----------------------------------------------------

    -> Thread Safety:

        -> Same partition:
            -> Sequential execution

        -> Different partitions:
            -> Parallel execution

        -> Shared data:
            -> Must be synchronized manually

    ----------------------------------------------------

    -> Performance Best Practices:

        -> Keep processing fast
        -> Avoid heavy logic inside event handler
        -> Use multiple consumer groups if needed

        -> Example:
            -> Group 1 → Storage
            -> Group 2 → Analytics

    ----------------------------------------------------

    -> Key Summary:

        -> Event Hubs scales using partitions
        -> Consumers scale horizontally
        -> Checkpoint ensures recovery
        -> SDK handles load balancing automatically

=> Control Access to Events (Azure Event Hubs)

    -> Why Access Control is Needed?

        -> Event Hubs handles sensitive streaming data
        -> We must ensure only authorized users/apps can:
            -> Send events
            -> Receive events
            -> Manage resources

    ----------------------------------------------------

    -> Authentication & Authorization Methods:

        -> 1. Microsoft Entra ID (Recommended)
        -> 2. Shared Access Signatures (SAS)

    ----------------------------------------------------

    -> 1. Azure RBAC Roles (Using Entra ID)

        -> Event Hubs supports built-in roles:

            -> Azure Event Hubs Data Owner
                -> Full access (send + receive + manage)

            -> Azure Event Hubs Data Sender
                -> Only send events

            -> Azure Event Hubs Data Receiver
                -> Only receive/read events

    ----------------------------------------------------

    -> Access using Managed Identity

        -> Managed Identity is linked to Azure resource

        -> Flow:

            App (Managed Identity)
                ↓
            Azure Role Assignment (RBAC)
                ↓
            Event Hubs Access Granted

        -> Benefit:
            -> No credentials stored in code
            -> Secure & automatic authentication

    ----------------------------------------------------

    -> Access using Microsoft Identity Platform (OAuth)

        -> Instead of storing secrets:

            -> App requests access token from Entra ID
            -> Entra ID authenticates user/app
            -> Returns OAuth 2.0 access token

        -> App uses token to access Event Hubs

        -> Key Benefit:
            -> No passwords or keys in code

    ----------------------------------------------------

    -> 2. Shared Access Signatures (SAS)

        -> What is SAS?

            -> A token-based authentication method
            -> Grants limited access to Event Hubs

        -> Key Concept:

            -> Each client gets a token
            -> Token defines what it can do (send/receive)

        -> Publisher Concept:

            -> Event Hub uses "publisher per client"
            -> Each publisher has a unique token

        -> Important:

            -> Client can only send to its assigned publisher
            -> Cannot access other publishers

    ----------------------------------------------------

    -> SAS Security Model:

        -> Tokens are signed using shared key
        -> Clients do NOT know the key
        -> Prevents fake token creation

        -> Tokens:
            -> Have expiry time
            -> Are reusable until expiration

    ----------------------------------------------------

    -> SAS for Consumers:

        -> Used for reading events

        -> Requires permissions:

            -> Listen OR Manage rights

        -> Scope levels:

            -> Namespace level
            -> Event Hub level

        -> Important limitation:

            -> SAS is NOT per consumer group
            -> It applies at entity level only

    ----------------------------------------------------

    -> Consumer Groups Security:

        -> Permissions apply to:
            -> Entire Event Hub or Namespace

        -> Not individually per consumer group

    ----------------------------------------------------

    -> Key Comparison:

        -> Entra ID (Recommended):
            -> Secure
            -> No secrets
            -> RBAC based

        -> SAS:
            -> Token based
            -> Less secure than Entra ID
            -> Uses shared keys

    ----------------------------------------------------

    -> Key Takeaways:

        -> Event Hubs security = Entra ID + SAS
        -> RBAC controls access using roles
        -> Managed identity removes need for secrets
        -> SAS uses tokens signed with shared key

=> Inspect Event Hubs
    -> Many Event Hubs operations take place within the scope of a specific partition.
    -> Because Event Hubs owns the partitions, their names are assigned at the time of creation.
    -> To understand what partitions are available, you query the Event Hubs using one of the Event Hubs clients.
    -> Example Client:
        -> EventHubProducerClient
        -> EventHubConsumerClient
        -> EventProcessorClient
    -> These client allow you to get partition IDs. read events, publish events and process events in scalable way.